I think you should try to meet people where they are. When you make chords you probably mostly use diatonic triads of the 12 tone equal temperament system in common cadences and voicings, just like everyone else. There are ways to subvert norms and cliches and introduce people to other sounds, but it doesn't involve wholesale avoidance of those norms. You can more effectively introduce people to the sounds you want them to hear by offering them music that is 80% the sounds they are used to and 20% other sounds you want them to hear. Then mix that resulting sound with 20% other sounds you want people to hear. And so on and so forth.

In regards to mixing, the foundation is sound selection. Especially your kick and bass need to work together. I've lost hours trying to get my kick sound good with EQ, sidechaining, compressing... but all I needed to do is simply choose another kick with a better transient. 80% of your "mixing" should be the volume fader. If you get sounds work together by simply adjusting the volume fader you need to decide which sound you should replace. If your kick cuts through the bass without any processing you have chosen the right one. The processing itself takes it from 8/10 to 10/10.

Drum sounds are repetitive as fuck, especially when you listen to the current trap rap and drill music. It's like all producers are sharing the same 5 drum kits. Creating your own is part of establishing your own style. Those drums sounds could be based on commonly used sounds but with your personal processing. You created a great snare for one of your tracks? Save it. Layered a great kick? Save it. This is how you end up with your personal drum kit, that sounds like you. My drum sounds are all my own, but it took me years to create my own library sampling real drum sounds from old records. I am currently sampling some 70s Russian progressive rock record that I would like to use for deep house.

What I do is start with the kick. I'll get my kick to sound just like I want it and peak at -12 db. This is my fixed point. I never touch the fader of the kick again. Everything else will get mixed around my kick as the anchor. At because it is the loudest element of my tracks I have my gain staging covered because everything else will be mixed lower in volume and I have more than enough headroom going into the master.

sounds very Clams Casino. however your drums are too weak. I'm gonna assume FL Studio here. get a break sample, and fruity slicex it. get some snappier snares, some chunkier kicks. check out Clams Casino (if you don't already know) for the type of drums that'd work well for this style.

your bass should be cutting through a bit more. it's sitting very far in the back of the mix. widen it out, bring it a bit more forward. bass should be a really solid foundation for everything else, not too thin. things are really hard to make out in general. It's pretty atmospheric, lots of pads and glittery sounds, but you need to EQ them better. they're all blending together in the mix. you should be able to hear every detail from all your sounds more, and if you have unwanted bass or high ends (unwanted bass in your pads for example), then eq that shit out.

Everything below 20 hz we can't hear anyway, so get rid of those. Now the question is what you track needs and what you can cut. I high pass around 20-45hz 12-24 db/oct without losing any energy. posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114298043
Yeah, some plugins have it even as a standard.
But consider the compouding effect. If your song has 60 individual tracks and half of them have unwanted frequencies that do not add to the character of the sound or they are not even audible, but at the end you forced to deal with them in the master channel. If you can cut for example muddy frequencies between 150-500 Hz without changing the character of the sound do it at the source instead of dealing with them later. Think also about the processing like delay/reverb/saturation you do with sounds and how they also add up in the mix.

>>114306668
Apologies for not getting back to you much sooner - I've been pretty sleep deprived and ended up crashing before I could write up some notes.

First off, I absolutely love the composition. Reminds me slightly of some of Jimmy Page's instrumental acoustic pieces, even if they're just studio outtakes or whatever. Warm, gentle, intimate, and (most importantly) hypnotic - put me in a comfy state of mind perfect for reflection. Enjoyed it enough to listen to it on loop while I wrote this up.

Recording sounds good, so no notes there. As for mixing, I thought it needed a little EQ and a lot more stereo separation, so I downloaded it and tried it out myself. I added:
>EQ (high-pass at 80 Hz, ~6 dB boost between 1-2k, and a gradual 6 dB increase from 2k-12k)
>stereo widening (+69% because it was very narrow before)
>true peak limiter (just to catch a stray peak or two in case I fucked up the gain somehow)

It might also be worth trying the following just to see if you like it better:
>hard=pan the two inputs (or just pan them dramatically)
>feed both into the same reverb send (sounding like they're in the same space will probably feel more natural for a solo acoustic recording)

Anyway, here's what I did to the roo. Hopefully I didn't ruin it.
https://voca.ro/1bM61L9R1gS0

No, but there's a tiny bit of truth to this. At its core, punk is protest music in the same sense as folkies like Woody Guthrie. It's really hard to write protest music about being a conservative who doesn't want anything to change, or being a liberal who wants slow, bureaucratic reforms. Protest music is most suitable to demanding radical change, which is why it's easiest to write protest songs from radical positions on the right and left.

That said, the truth is probably most punk isn't really very articulate about its political vision, and there are a lot of apolitical bands who just kind of did punk as a style or artistic statement.

posts.com:
I'm pretty sure pretty much everyone's gotten it wrong so far.

>punk
This is more conventionally rock music in structure than hardcore. It has the conventional choruses. It tends to be simpler than most other rock genres, but isn't always - sometimes it's noisy and attacks rock conventions by dabbling in the avant-garde, which is when it starts to lean toward "art punk." It typically has a "snotty" attitude. Songs are usually the normal length of rock songs, lasting between about 2 1/2 and 4 minutes. Standard examples include the Ramones, the Sex Pistols, Richard Hell & The Voidoids.

>hardcore
This is where it begins to lose the conventional rock structure. There's typically no more conventional "verse-chorus" structure. The vocals are yelled instead of sung, the guitars are heavier/thicker, songs tend to be about 1 1/2 minutes, and it tends to be angrier than standard punk. It often has a "tough guy" mentality. Later hardcore developed its own structures, like breakdowns, where everything slows down so the audience can mosh. It also looks a lot different - where punk has an extravagant look, with piercings, spiky hair, a leather jacket, etc., hardcore is almost the opposite. Clothes become functional, like gym shorts, plain t-shirts, shaved heads, etc. It's debatable whether Dead Kennedys are punk or hardcore, and people shouldn't be looking to them as an example because they were so unique. A much better example of the standard hardcore sound is Minor Threat.

>metalcore
As hardcore went on, it got heavier and heavier, and some of the musicians became more ambitious, so they started to incorporate guitar styles associated with thrash metal and extreme metal. The sound got a lot thicker, and it was no longer just simple rock. Examples include Hatebreed and Converge.

(1/2)

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114313632
>pop punk
While some punk became a lot more challenging to rock conventions, other bands put a snotty, rebellious spin on 60s pop rock and bubblegum, essentially. They wanted to sing catchy, fun songs about being outsiders. this goes all the way back to the beginning of the genre, with bands like the Ramones, the Buzzcocks, Blondie, and The Undertones writing twisted pop songs with dark humor. Later pop punk bands were actually rooted in hardcore's unpretentious, grounded style, like Descendents, who in turn inspired bands that had a bigger, more commercial sound, like Green Day. Pop Punk usually but not always abandons punk's rougher, "DIY" aesthetic.

>grunge
The Seattle grunge scene was a sort of melting pot between early heavy metal, 70s hard rock, and alternative/indie/punk in the late 80s. Guitars were typically sludgy, songs tended to be less political than punk and more about personal feelings, and it was closely related to other trends in the 80s underground like noise rock and post-hardcore, which themselves were experimental outgrowths of the punk/hardcore scene. The most famous examples are obviously bands like Nirvana, but if you want the core, defining grunge sound, the easiest thing to point to is probably Mudhoney.

>post-hardcore
These are bands rooted in hardcore, who wanted to do more experimental, ambitious things. By the mid 80s, many people were bored with just playing extremely simple hardcore, which they'd done for years. So they began to experiment with structure, noise, songwriting, even sometimes incorporating jazz elements. Examples include Fugazi, Hüsker Dü, NoMeansNo, Jawbox.

No. New York Hardcore is nearly 20 years older than nu metal. However, it probably is an underrecognized influence on nu metal.

New York has always been out of sync with other punk scenes. NY punk's first wave was a little earlier than everyone else, then it kind of died when punk was big in London and LA because the New York bands were touring, and the punk scene kind of degraded into an art music scene, which isn't necessarily a bad thing (there's a great film about that period called Downtown 81). The New York Hardcore scene took a while to get going, then once the first wave of hardcore basically ended and bands were starting to drift to alternative rock, the NYHC bands got a lot louder, tougher, and more metallic, which laid the groundwork for a lot of crossover thrash and metalcore. They also had a hip hop swagger, Madball being a key example.

>>114314253
Disagree slightly. Discharge were a huge influence on crust, but crust is different from d-beat in attitude and focus (though a lot of crust bands use the actual d-beat drumming style). If the street punk and anarcho-punk scenes were on different sides in the 80s, Discharge was firmly in the middle, but the crust bands were way over on the anarcho side. Musically they tend to be slower and darker than most d-beat, with a more pronounced post-punk component, and stronger connections to styles like black metal, death metal, and sludge metal. The lyrical themes also tend to be a lot more pessimistic than d-beat, which often has a more rocking attitude. I'd recommend comparing Discharge to something like Deviated Instinct to see the difference.

>>114304801
I was being flippant and not serious when I said ? & The Mysterians invented punk. It was a play on the bait comment about Death. I know there were other garage rock bands around at the time. I think ? & The Mysterians may have been the first band to actually have the term punk applied to them, but I recognize that doesn't really make them any more punk than a band like The Kingsmen.

If you ask me, no one person or band invented punk, it was an underground club scene, with bands doing unconventional, anti-establishment things together, that led to punk. Maybe it was a sensibility. But it was the Ramones fusing garage rock, bubblegum pop, and sick humor, AND it was The Neon Boys/Television/Richard Hell making avant-garde, poetic, nihilistic, post-Velvet Underground noise, AND it was The Dictators making offensive anti-rockstar metal.

I think if one band is more responsible than anyone for punk, though, it has to be The Stooges. They were so violent and primal, live and especially on Funhouse. They switched to being so thrashy and fast on Raw Power. I also think it's worth paying attention to the entire Detroit scene, which was sort of garage rock, but it was louder and more aggressive than the entire rest of the genre. It obviously included The Stooges and the MC5, but it also included Alice Cooper, The Amboy Dukes (Ted Nugent's original band), and this is where Death comes in (which is really why they're notable - they were a lost gem of a proto-punk scene, not an influence).

There were plenty of other precedents, though. There were the early New York bands like the New York Dolls, Suicide, and The Fugs, who had a rough, simple, nihilistic approach that upset rock conventions. There were great avant-garde bands, from avant-garage figures like Captain Beefheart and The Monks to the "krautrock" scene with Can, Faust, etc....

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114244763
It's harder than it seems (and it does seem difficult) to get longer/progressive tracks to work in video games. They tend to be hilariously distracting and immersion-breaking whenever there is blatant mismatch with the action or, most insidiously, the lack thereof. At that point you have to design the game around the music rather than the other way around.
Moreover, the prog influence was already fizzling out by the time it was just barely feasible in terms of technical limitations and design repertoire to have a 10+ minute game event that remains interesting throughout.

>>114282823
They didn't need to.
But to try to give a more serious answer, they weren't a "traditional" prog band. They get labeled as progressive rock because, of all the established overarching genre classifications, it's the one that suits them best, but they didn't follow many of the genre's common tropes. Which is why I believe a lot of people are initially turned off by them or have difficulty understanding what they were going for. Most prog bands were interested in epic, escapist, dramatic songwriting, while Gentle Giant's gimmick was creating intricate music puzzles.
